# Ether Application Engine Documentation {#ether-application-engine-documentation}

# 1\.  Introduction {#1.-introduction}

## 1.1 Purpose {#1.1-purpose}

The purpose of this document is to provide a high-level architecture representation of BBVA’s Ether Application Engine platform..

## 1.2 Scope {#1.2-scope}

This document encompasses the Ether Application Engine components. The relationship between Ether Application Engine and other PaaS components is presented here as well. The remaining Ether Platform subsystems (DaaS, IaaS, SEMaaS, SECaaS, etc.) will be referenced when applicable but will not be addressed.

## 1.3 Intended Audience {#1.3-intended-audience}

This document is targeted at readers who need to understand the component parts of a specific discipline in the platform. Intended audience includes  IT executives and non-technical resources. While diagrams and component definitions must employ a certain amount of technical terminology, this deliverable is intended for its use and understanding by teams at all levels.

For high level definitions of technical terms, a glossary is available for reference in the following [link](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1ulDIbrXsl_GVS6DH9LeL4hbDKQL_ay693S2optuhXQc).

## 1.4 Overview {#1.4-overview}

This document’s main concern is to address Ether’s PaaS architecture documentation. It starts with a static view which identifies the most significant components with their purpose, responsibilities and the relationships between them. Afterwards, a dynamic view will be presented, including the most relevant component interactions in the PaaS, and presenting other illustrative representations deemed useful for the reader.

# 2\. Ether Application Engine Architectural Overview {#2.-ether-application-engine-architectural-overview}

## 2.1 What is Ether Application Engine {#2.1-what-is-ether-application-engine}

Ether Application Engine (EAE) is one of the core elements of PaaS, in fact it is the component where the applications run. EAE automatically and in standardized format provides the underlying cloud infrastructure including network, servers, operating systems, or storage.

EAE is a core subsystem in Ether platform. EAE is the name of the Ether PaaS. A PaaS is a cloud platform allowing users to develop, run and manage applications without the complexity of building and maintaining the infrastructure typically associated with developing and launching an app. Developers do not need to worry about provisioning resources for their applications or understand the underlying technical complexity of the bank. It provides and abstracts the networks, servers, storage, OS, 'runtimes' (e.g. APX) and other services which are necessary to build and host applications and expose services.

In addition to storage and other computing resources, users are able to use a suite of prebuilt tools to develop, customize and test their own applications.

## 2.2 PaaS \[Ether Application Engine\] Objectives {#2.2-paas-[ether-application-engine]-objectives}

The PaaS platform was designed with the following objectives in mind:

* To provide tools to develop, test and host applications in one single platform 

* To facilitate collaborative work, locally and globally

* To enable developers to focus on development without having to worry about underlying infrastructure

* To enable a flexible, streamlined app life-cycle with faster time to value

* To provide scalable, strategically data-centred, cloud native apps

## 2.3 PaaS \[EAE\] Roles {#2.3-paas-[eae]-roles}

Different actors interact with the PaaS platform to execute tasks which are inherent to their team or department. The following main roles have been identified:

| PaaS Role | Role Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| PaaS Application Developer | Responsible for completing the application and component development life-cycle. |
| PaaS Solution Architect | Responsible for provisioning the application space in the PaaS and the supporting components. Designs the application so it fits within the rest of the services offering, both functionally and technically. |
| PaaS Administrator | Responsible for configuring and administering the PaaS internal engine to ensure proper functioning of serviced apps at all times. |
| Application User | Uses the PaaS applications deployed as services. |
| PaaS Runtime Administrator | Responsible for managing runtimes (e.g. APX)  images, update runtimes and runtime configurations and extracting statistics. |

## 2.4 PaaS \[EAE\] Responsibilities {#2.4-paas-[eae]-responsibilities}

The purpose of a PaaS is to provide all the necessary supporting technologies to enable application as a service deployments and use. BBVA’s Ether PaaS is responsible for:

1. Providing access points for various interacting actors, as identified in the Roles section  
2. Allowing new application product  provisioning, including Bitbucket, UA and product resources  
3. Allowing for application deployment (and use) as a service  
4. Allowing for application horizontal and vertical scaling in order to meet performance requirements  
5. Providing all necessary security measures to enforce BBVA Enterprise Global and Local Policies  
6. Providing all necessary monitoring and alerting systems to comply with BBVA Enterprise SLAs and standards  
7. Providing the adequate, supporting cloud-enabled technology for application as a service deployments, in a way that complies with BBVA’s requirements in terms of:  
   1. Governance constraints  
   2. Legal Requirements  
   3. Service Level Agreements  
   4. Business Continuity Planning  
   5. User Access Policy  
   6. Data Safety and Security  
   7. All other enterprise policies, at a Global and/or Country level

## 2.5 PaaS System Context {#2.5-paas-system-context}

The PaaS subsystem interacts directly with the IaaS subsystem to execute workloads, and with the SECaaS subsystem where it delegates security concerns. Additionally, it is directly used by Applications and several actors, such as the Application Developer, the PaaS Solution Architect, the PaaS Administrator and the PaaS Runtime Administrator.

# 3\. Components Description {#3.-components-description}

## 3.1 EAE Component Diagram {#3.1-eae-component-diagram}

Ether’s Ether Application Engine is composed of several related components that enable the PaaS Cloud offering at BBVA. These components can be classified according to six categories with the following components:

![][image2]

Figure 2 – EAE Component Domains

* ***End-user:*** Console & Catalog components, main entry points for PaaS developers and administrators  
* ***Middleware:*** Waveform component, core architecture element of the PaaS, responsible for orchestrating application deployments and interactions  
* ***DevTools:*** Docker Management & DevTools components, assisting technologies and software supporting the Core PaaS Component Orchestration  
* ***Monitoring***: EFK (Elasticsearch, Fluentd, Kibana) and Prometheus components, which are foundational cross components potentially involved at all levels in the PaaS architecture  
* ***Security*****:** Armadillo, Chimera, Lux, Vats and Sebasshtian which are security cross components   
* ***Networking***: This domain contains the components needed to provide PaaS services to consumers in an efficient way, balanced with HA servers and secured via a reverse proxy as unique point of entry


![paascomponentdiagram.png][image3]

Figure 3 – PaaS Component Diagram

## 3.2 End-user Components {#3.2-end-user-components}

### ![][image4]

Figure 4 – PaaS End-User Component Diagram

### 3.2.1 Console {#3.2.1-console}

**Description**

The Console is used as an administrative GUI to deploy and provision new applications. It is the main access point to the rest of the PaaS components, both for the PaaS administration team and for the development users. It communicates directly with Waveform through a HTTP API and, depending on user permissions, allows the execution of a series of actions, listed in the responsibilities section below.

**Responsibilities**

The Console responsibilities and features include:

* Provisioning of new application projects, including the request of an application code repository and the UUAA setup   
* Selecting the APIs, runtimes and other applications that applications are going to consume  
* Administering application life-cycles, including versioning, configuration and deployment  
* Generating/creating descriptors (YAML) defining application ecosystems and deployment requirements  
* Requesting more resources for a given application (scaling)  
* Providing access to other productivity applications used by the developers in their daily tasks

## 3.3 Middleware Components {#3.3-middleware-components}

![][image5]

Figure 5 – PaaS Middleware Component Diagram

### 3.3.1 Waveform {#3.3.1-waveform}

**Description**

Waveform is responsible for the orchestration of application deployments and interactions.

It is an in-house component that communicates with EClusters through a REST API to deploy containers – Docker images stored in the Artifactory – according to the instructions it receives from the Console.

EClusters are the set of machines over which Waveform deploys PaaS application containers. They are an essential part of the cloud platform that allows PaaS users to deploy new applications on secure, scalable resources with minimal configuration and management overhead. 

**Responsibilities**

Waveform is responsible for:

* Using descriptors to deploy groups of baselined and inter-connected applications  
* Orchestrating the deployment and provisioning of containers on EClusters  
* Promoting applications between environments

## 3.4 Monitoring and logging Components {#3.4-monitoring-and-logging-components}

![][image6]

Figure 6 – PaaS Monitoring Component Diagram

Ether Application Engine has:

- Platform monitoring and logging: used by platform administrators  
- Application monitoring and logging: used by the owners of the applications to see how their applications are running.

The platform has nodes, each has FluentD Agent. Outside  of these nodes there is a FluentD aggregator. It collects the data and sends logs to:

- Elasticsearch (Kibana is its front-end)   
- SEMaaS: FluentD also writes EAE information to a monitoring component of SEMaaS  
- Kafka queue, where currently developers check application logs. In the future application logs will be sent to SEMaaS

In the PaaS, Elasticsearch works in integration with Fluentd (log aggregation tool) and Kibana (used for displaying the information) to provide monitoring capabilities. The three tools together compose what is known as the EFK stack, and allow the PaaS administration team to control the platform for an early detection of errors. In order for the EFK to fulfill its objective, agents that push the logs to the stack are installed on client systems. Applications deployed by developers are not watched by EFK.

EFK receives admin/system logs from Waveform and Prometheus. Other logs such as the applicative container logs are currently still redirected to a legacy logging system, and should be integrated with SEMaaS in the future.

The following sections describe Elasticsearch, Fluentd, Kibana and Prometheus in more detail.

### 3.4.1 Elasticsearch {#3.4.1-elasticsearch}

**Description**

Elasticsearch is a distributed, RESTful search and analytics engine capable of centrally storing data, such as logs and metrics, so that it can later be explored and visualized.

**Responsibilities**

Elasticsearch is responsible for:

* Receiving aggregated logs from Fluentd  
* Indexing the logs  
* Searching through the logs

### 3.4.2. Fluentd {#3.4.2.-fluentd}

**Description**

Fluentd is an open source data collector, which lets you unify data collection and consumption for a better use and understanding of data. It decouples data sources from backend systems by providing a unified logging layer in between. 

In the PaaS, it works as a log aggregator, sending the information it receives to Elasticsearch, for its exploration. 

**Responsibilities**

Fluentd is responsible for:

* Receiving logs from Waveform, EClusters, Prometheus and the Artifactory  
* Aggregating the logs and sending them to Elasticsearch

### 3.4.3. Kibana {#3.4.3.-kibana}

**Description**

Kibana is an open-source data visualization and exploration tool used for log and time series analytics, application monitoring, and operational intelligence use cases. Kibana offers tight integration with Elasticsearch, an analytics and search engine, which provides Kibana with data stored visualization capabilities. Kibana also has powerful and easy-to-use features such as histograms, line graphs, pie charts, heat maps and built-in geospatial support.

Kibana is a data visualization and exploration platform from Elastic that is specialized in large volumes of streaming and real-time data. 

**Responsibilities**

Kibana responsibilities and features include:

* Acting as a visualization solution for the logs and metrics which are stored in Elasticsearch.

### 3.4.4 Prometheus  {#3.4.4-prometheus}

**Description**

Prometheus is a monitoring component used by the PaaS administration team. It monitors and sends alerts by polling the health status and other metrics from Waveform, Artifactory and EClusters, using HTTP APIs. Prometheus communicates with the Slack channel to inform the teams.

**Responsibilities**

Prometheus is responsible for alerting administrators and other relevant users when a problem arises in the components of the PaaS. Applications deployed by developers are not monitored by Prometheus.

### 3.4.5 Grafana  {#3.4.5-grafana}

**Description**

Grafana allows queries, visualization, alerting and understanding of business metrics, to create, explore, and share dashboards with teams and foster a data driven culture.

**Responsibilities**

Visualize the data collected and monitored by Prometheus

## 3.5 DevTools: Tools Components  {#3.5-devtools:-tools-components}

![][image7]

Figure 7 – PaaS DevTools and Automation Component Diagram

DevTools is a group of development tools used to create, test and deliver applications over the Ether Platform.

The DevTools stack is composed of the following, independent but connected, software:

#### **Jenkins** {#jenkins}

Jenkins is a continuous integration tool used by PaaS developers to test, build and deploy Bitbucket source code into Docker images that will later be stored in Artifactory.  Therefore Jenkins is for the continuous integration of applications. It constantly integrates application codebases and starts multiple-step pipelines of actions when specific events happen. 

#### **Kubernetes** {#kubernetes}

While Jenkins pipeline creates an image, it is Kubernetes software that automates the deployment of the created image.

#### **Bitbucket** {#bitbucket}

Bitbucket provides a distributed Git (Version Control System) repository along with some productivity tools and integrations for programmers (CI/CD).

#### **Artifactory** {#artifactory}

Artifactory is the repository where all the Docker images are stored.

#### **Slack** {#slack}

Slack is a communication platform for teams which allows for chat, notifications and alerts to be set up. In particular, the PaaS Administration team uses it for monitoring purposes.

#### **Concourse** {#concourse}

It is the CI/CD tool that the PaaS Administration team uses for container tests and deployments. Concourse is a Continuous Integration server used for continuous integration of the platform.  

#### **Responsibilities** {#responsibilities}

The DevTools stack assures that programmers can create and deploy applications. In particular, it has the following responsibilities:

1. Hosting source code and managing versioning. Enables collaborative and distributed programming  
2. Facilitating team collaboration  
3. Storing and managing external libraries versions  
4. Orchestrating build pipelines: builds components and Docker images, stores them in Artifactory  
5. Orchestrating tests and deployments of components and applications

## 3.6 Networking Components {#3.6-networking-components}

![networking.png][image8]

Figure 8 – PaaS Networking Component Diagram

### 3.6.1 BIND {#3.6.1-bind}

**Description**

Server that manages the correlation between IP addresses and their associated hostnames. BIND is the translator between the hostname and IP address.

This server covers the internal ANS service. Currently, this server is allocated in the BOOTSTRAP machine.

**Responsibilities**

The BIND responsibilities and features include:

* It keeps the correlation between IP addresses and their associated hostnames internally in the tenant or environment 

### 3.6.2 HAProxy {#3.6.2-haproxy}

**Description**

This component provides a high availability load balancer to balance any requests from customers to the backend servers.

**Responsibilities**

* It balances each customer request done from any communication channel  
* It distributes the workload across multiple servers  
* It provides Access Control List (ACL) management, flexibilizing the network traffic forwarding, based on a variety of factors like pattern-matching and the number of connections to a backend  
* It provides different types of Load Balancing; the following are some examples: **Round Robin**: selects servers in turns, **leastconn**: selects the server with the least number of connections (recommended for longer sessions), **source:** selects which server to use based on a hash of the source IP.

### 3.6.3 NTP {#3.6.3-ntp}

**Description**

The NTP is an operating-system daemon that sets and maintains a computer system's time in synchronization with Internet-standard time servers.

**Responsibilities**

The NTP’s main responsibility is to make sure all machines are displaying the exact same time.

## 3.7 Security Components  {#3.7-security-components}

![][image9]

Figure 9 – SECaaS Components used by PaaS \- Component Diagram.

### 3.7.1 Security Stack {#3.7.1-security-stack}

PaaS Security is delegated to the SECaaS subsystem, which makes security components available for use across the Ether Platform. SECaaS components are used to enforce protection against specific internal and external security threats in the PaaS, following BBVA’s enterprise policies and recommendations. 

The security layer is present between Waveform and the Console, and also between the Internet and application services (which may later be handled by a specific API Gateway component). These layers enforce protection against specific internal and external security threats

Currently, the following SECaaS components are used in the PaaS domain. ***For a more detailed description of the SECaaS components, please refer to the SECaaS documentation***:

- **Armadillo**: Armadillo is an API Security Gateway that protects APIs both at Authentication (AuthN) and Authorization (AuthZ) level. It sits just before the Apps, inspecting and protecting all the traffic that goes in. It can delegate the Authentication to Serval and the authorization to Lux Components  
- **Nauthilus**: it is an identity provider solution based on SAML 2.0 protocol, designed to work in a modular way so it can delegate some of the traditional idp tasks (user attributes retrieving, authentication, authorization, etc.), to external and dedicated systems in order to tailor a whole customized authentication/authorization solution, and is able to validate identities received. it delegates the credentials validation to SERVAL, and the Authorization to LUX  
- **SerVal**: This component is on charge of credential validation, so it supports the customer authentication  
- **Lux**: authorization component containing rules & policies to allow or deny the user access to the requested service. It is a single policy control point for the entire enterprise. Before granting access to anyone or anything, LUX creates a contextual identity. It inspects user, time, location, kind of device and environment variables in general, then it applies the relevant policy to control which resource can access   
- **Chameleon**: Chameleon is an adaptive cryptographic platform that allows: automated management of encryption, decryption and data aggregation processes; automated management of service certificates; automated management of cryptographic keys; and protection of data stored in transit according to their nature  
- **Chimera**: Component that verifies the Docker images content, to ensure the authenticity of these, in order to prevent corrupted or manipulated images. It is in charge of docker management  
- **Vats**: Agent that verifies security in an installation, at OS and infrastructure level, checking vulnerabilities in the OS, ports, etc.  
- **Sebasshtian**: It is a SSH Server which protects the subsystem from other components. It is a Bastion Host to protect access to the internal net. This component audits Ether users’ access. Admin users access the platform through this component.

# 4\. Components Relationships {#4.-components-relationships}

This section presents the most significant components in the PaaS and their relationships. 

The Architecture Overview presented in section 2.5 introduced these components, grouped into simplified conceptual domains. The following relationship diagram extends the Overview to present the nature of each one of the relations:

![][image10]

Figure 4 – PaaS Component Relationship Diagram

## 4.1 Component Relationship Descriptions {#4.1-component-relationship-descriptions}

### 4.1.1 From End-user Components {#4.1.1-from-end-user-components}

#### **Console – Bitbucket** {#console-–-bitbucket}

The Console is the main entry point to PaaS, both for development and administration users. It uses Bitbucket for the provisioning of new application projects, including the request of a git application code repository.

#### **Console – Waveform** {#console-–-waveform}

The Console is the component through which developers and administrators can access Waveform. It allows them to manage the deployment of Docker application images on EClusters, giving them the possibility to promote or recover versions, as well as specify the resources they wish to allocate. 

#### **Console – Catalog (future)** {#console-–-catalog-(future)}

In the future, the Console will be able to search the Catalog through an API.

### 4.1.2 From Monitoring Components {#4.1.2-from-monitoring-components}

#### **Prometheus – EFK, Waveform, Artifactory** {#prometheus-–-efk,-waveform,-artifactory}

Prometheus is a monitoring and alerting tool used by the PaaS administration team. It consumes metrics from EFK and polls Artifactory, Waveform and EClusters for information.


#### **EFK – Waveform, EClusters, Artifactory, Prometheus** {#efk-–-waveform,-eclusters,-artifactory,-prometheus}

EFK consumes logs from Waveform, EClusters, Artifactory and Prometheus, exposing metrics and allowing the PaaS administration team to monitor the functioning of these PaaS components. 

Fluentd is an agent installed in every PaaS machine, and publishes logs to Kafka R2, SEMaaS and Elasticsearch.

#### **Prometheus – Slack** {#prometheus-–-slack}

Prometheus communicates with the Slack channel to inform the teams

### 4.1.3 From Orchestration Components {#4.1.3-from-orchestration-components}

#### **Waveform – Artifactory** {#waveform-–-artifactory}

Waveform communicates with Artifactory and accesses the Docker images contained in it to verify they can be deployed.

#### **Waveform – EClusters** {#waveform-–-eclusters}

Waveform communicates with EClusters through a REST API to deploy containers according to YAML descriptors. These descriptors are provided through the Console.

### 4.1.4 From Tools Components {#4.1.4-from-tools-components}

#### **Bitbucket – Jenkins (not PaaS)** {#bitbucket-–-jenkins-(not-paas)}

Although they are not essentially PaaS components, the relationship between Bitbucket and Jenkins is key in the creation of the Docker image which is later stored in Artifactory. When a developer executes a push on his repository, this triggers the Jenkins pipeline which is responsible for the automated testing and packaging of the code. 

#### **Jenkins – Artifactory** {#jenkins-–-artifactory}

Once the Docker image has been created, Jenkins sends it to Artifactory to be stored through the Docker CLI action step.

#### **Concourse – Waveform, EClusters Prometheus, Artifactory** {#concourse-–-waveform,-eclusters-prometheus,-artifactory}

Concourse is the component used by the PaaS administration team for the automated testing and deployment of other PaaS components containers: Waveform, EClusters, Prometheus and the Artifactory. It also communicates with the Slack channel to inform the teams about builds.

### 4.1.4 From Security Components {#4.1.4-from-security-components}

#### **Sebasshtian \- PaaS**  {#sebasshtian---paas}

Sebasshtian is a Host Bastion that allows or denies access to the internal net, acting as the proxy to access and deploy applications containers into the PaaS. Sebasshtian provides SSH access to the PaaS infrastructure in order to deploy and maintain applications and associated infrastructure.

#### **Armadillo – Waveform**  {#armadillo-–-waveform}

Armadillo is used to protect PaaS and PaaS-related components such as Waveform. Waveform, on the other side, orchestrates the Security Stack components.  
Armadillo enables the authentication at application and services level. As Waveform is a PaaS service that provides utilities to manage the PaaS components, it has to be secured, and this securitization is done with Armadillo.

#### **Armadillo – Lux**  {#armadillo-–-lux}

Armadillo enables the authentication at application and services level, but it does not have authorization capabilities. Instead, they are provided by the Lux component, so Armadillo delegates the authorization to Lux. 

#### **Lux \- Waveform**  {#lux---waveform}

As was explained in the relation between Armadillo-Waveform, this relation (Lux-Waveform) is analogous but at the Authorization level, that is, Waveform is secured by Lux to profile the Lux users access.

#### **Chimera \- Artifactory**  {#chimera---artifactory}

Artifactory is the binary repository for Docker images, and Chimera validates the authenticity of those images, so, there is a direct relation between both components. In the software deployment process, once the images are extracted from Artifactory, Chimera validates them, before doing the delivery to the production environment

## 5.1 Image Management {#5.1-image-management}

The image management family regroups flows explaining how **PaaS and Runtime Administrators** manage Base Docker Images and make them available for **Application Developer** teams.

### 5.1.1 Runtime (Base) Image Build {#5.1.1-runtime-(base)-image-build}

In the containerized architecture of the PaaS, base images are cardinal artifacts that enable component and application deployment. Administrative resources (**PaaS Administrators**) build them and deploy them in the Artifactory, so developers can later use them in their applications.

The base image build process always starts with the creation of a single descriptor file called Dockerfile. This descriptor contains the instructions for the Docker engine as to what libraries are to be included in the image artifact. After the Dockerfile is created, it is stored in a Bitbucket repository. The administrator then starts a Concourse pipeline manually, that will initiate the docker build sequence to finally store the image in the Artifactory when the creation process is complete.

![][image11]

Descriptor file is created by the Runtime teams. Knowledge of the instructions contained in the descriptor file are important for the developers, because the developers image is going to run on top the base image that  the runtime team has provided. The  application developer can look at the already preconfigured descriptor file in the repository to be knowledgeable of all that is going on in the background, to create an application that makes the best use of the preconfigured resources.  The base image gives the developer a virtualized server with its operating system and everything. The developer needs to know what is there, for example, that provisioned with the base image is an application server, the configuration of the access to the databases.

## 5.2 Creation of application by developers {#5.2-creation-of-application-by-developers}

This process group describes the general flows illustrating how **Application Developers** create applications using the PaaS, with the help of **Solution Architects** and using the base images created by **Runtime Administrators.**

### 5.2.1 Application Setup {#5.2.1-application-setup}

The first step to set up a new application in the PaaS is for the Solution Architect to create a Product in the Console. A product is a logical entity which groups applications. Once the product has been created, applications can be defined by System Architecs and components can be added for each application. For every component, a Bitbucket repository is created, with a specified runtime. Components have an associated docker image stored in the Artifactory. BitBucket stores code, while Artifactory stores images, artifacts, and created pieces.

Applications don’t have traffic until all of their components have been set up. Applications are the minimum deployment units, i.e. a component cannot be deployed on its own. Components are the minimum unit for escalation.

![][image12]

### 5.2.2 Application Development {#5.2.2-application-development}

After projects and applications are provisioned by the **Solution Architects**, **Application Developers** may start working on their repositories and build the application. They will use Bitbucket (git) distributed repositories to store and manage the source code, as well as the application configuration descriptor. 

The typical coding workflow involves code submissions from their end (commit \+ push), and approval on the side of a privileged developer in the project. This approver is in charge of reviewing the changes in the baseline to either approve and integrate them, or reject them.

![][image13]

### 5.2.3 Application Image Build {#5.2.3-application-image-build}

**Application Developers** build their applications into Docker images, based on Docker runtime images which provide the libraries they need in their apps.

After the developer ships a change in an application (commit \+ push) and the change is accepted (merged into the repository), Jenkins detects the change automatically and starts a build pipeline. This pipeline consists of a series of steps such as download of the code, compilation, testing etc. If all the steps are completed successfully, a Docker image representing a deployable artifact for the application is created and stored into the Artifactory. Even though the pipeline performs its actions automatically, it is interesting for the developer to be knowledge of the steps and processes contained  in the pipeline.

![][image14]

### 5.2.4 Application Image Deployment {#5.2.4-application-image-deployment}

Here the developer deploys the application they have created in an application environment (DEV, INT, QA, PRO). When **Application Developers** define that the application images are ready, they manually start another Jenkins pipeline designed to deploy the image into an environment of their choice. Each application contains a descriptor which specifies some parameters including the environment where it should be deployed. The descriptor file is selected by the developer in the console. It comes with the preconfigured values of the runtime and can be edited by the developer. Jenkins passes this descriptor to Waveform, which in turn communicates with EClusters to execute the deployment.

![][image15]

### 5.2.5 Application Scaling {#5.2.5-application-scaling}

Applications executing in the PaaS are dimensioned using the descriptor described earlier (see sections 5.2.2 and 5.2.4). In this descriptor, **Application Developers** may define the resources they wish to allocate to the applications, such as memory or number of nodes. 

When an application is deployed, developers could eventually decide to adjust the resources. Since the PaaS does not currently embed any auto-scaling mechanisms, developers have to edit the descriptors and “republish” them from the console so that the PaaS team becomes aware of the new resource requirements and proceeds to scaling the app accordingly (no downtime involved).

**![][image16]**

## 5.3 Logging, Monitoring and Alerting {#5.3-logging,-monitoring-and-alerting}

This group of flows explains how the logs and metrics generated by PaaS components are handled in the PaaS by tools such as Prometheus and EFK.

### 5.3.1 Component Monitoring and Alerting {#5.3.1-component-monitoring-and-alerting}

Prometheus is the tool that polls the PaaS internal components for health metrics monitoring.

When these metrics change and break the thresholds set by the administrators, a series of alerts may be emitted by Prometheus to inform the resources responsible for components’ maintenance.

![][image17]

### 5.3.2 Component Logging {#5.3.2-component-logging}

Some internal PaaS components and applications organize their critical logs in dedicated files. These applications may live with a linked EFK agent, which pushes the news from these critical logs to EFK in the PaaS, thus allowing for the indexing and reporting of errors. Elasticsearch, Fluentd, and Kibana (EFK) allow you to collect, index, search, and visualize log data.

![][image18]

# 6\. Ether Application Engine Deployment {#6.-ether-application-engine-deployment}

This section describes how the Ether Application Engine team does deployment of the components of the platform. In other words, it gives a snapshot of the deployment of components needed for the platform to exist. An example of EAE deployment is when EAE deploys a new version of Waveform.

## 6.1. Requesting Tenants {#6.1.-requesting-tenants}

Each PaaS tenant is based on the same infrastructure, and it could be described as follows:

* When the PaaS team requests a tenant to the IaaS, the IaaS team build the tenant base on the PaaS’s requirements, in terms of: CPU, Processors, RAM, etc. Then the IaaS Team deliver the tenant to PaaS.  
* The tenant only has a virtual network created by the IaaS, and the computational capabilities requested.  
* The Ether Core Application Engine team creates the networks and components required for the tenant, using the API provided by IaaS and orchestrating the recreation with “Ansible” cloud.  
* To scale the PaaS infrastructure the procedure is currently manual, and if the tenant is full the PaaS’s Team has to request an upgrade of IaaS’s Team. 

## 6.2. Platform Environments and Networks {#6.2.-platform-environments-and-networks}

There are two platform environments per country for the Ether Core Application Engine team:

* Work: The natural environment for PaaS Teams, being the most volatile of all.  
* Live: The most stable production environment.

In the future there may be an additional environment: Play.

Here is a description of the installations we have and how they are used in the networks. It shows how tenants are connected to the networks. Each country is connected to two networks.

1. Work environment is connected to the DEV (development) network of Tres Cantos data center: We have the development network of Tres Cantos that only has access to the Work host and the Work databases of Tres Cantos. Tenants plugged to the Work network of Tres cantos are:  
* There is a Platform Work tenant plugged to the Work network in Tres Cantos. 

* There is a Work Spain tenant

* There is a Tools Work tenant inside which are modules , such as concourse, etc.

2. Work environment is connected to the DEV (development) network of Lago Esmeralda data center: We have the development network of Lago Esmeralda that only has access to the Work host and the Work databases of Lago Esmeralda. Tenants plugged to the work network of Lago Esmeralda are:  
* There is a Platform Work tenant plugged to the Work network in Lago Esmeralda.

* There is a Work tenant for each country: Mexico, Peru, USA and in the future Chile and Colombia.

* There is a Tools Work tenant inside which are modules , such as concourse, etc.

3. Live environment is connected to the PRO (production) network of Tres Cantos data center: Tenants plugged to the production network of the Tres Cantos data center are:  
* Platform Live tenant of Tres Cantos

* Spain Live tenant

* Tools Live Tres Cantos

4. Live environment is connected to the PRO (production) network (Data center) Lago Esmeralda  
* Platform Live tenant of Lago Esmeralda

* One Live tenant per country: Mexico, Peru, USA.

* Tools Live tenant Lago Esmeralda

The important concept here is to note that development and production are on separate networks. They never cross. There are no machines connected to both. For example, it is not possible to have a tenant of development connected to the production network.

The networks are physically isolated.

In summary, Ether Core Application Engine can use several tenants for the same environment. For example, the environment Live can have one tenant for the platform (i.e. OCP) and another for tools (i.e. Concourse).

The users of the platform in its environments, do not need to know about the tenants that make up the platform.

## 6.3. PaaS Tenants Creation Process {#6.3.-paas-tenants-creation-process}

Deployment of a PaaS component is done in modules. The creation of the tenants by modules is an automatic process. Modules are grouped in systems that serve a purpose.

The process of creation of tenants produces several instances within the tenant. An instance is a program, a piece of software based on a module. For example, the process may create a Bastion instance, which is an instance of the Bastion module, within the tenant.

Each Tenant has several instances.  An instance is a program, therefore it can be a module. For example the tenant might contain an instance of the database Cassandra. OpenStack Instances are virtual machines that run inside the cloud. They are launched from images.

Tenants have many pieces. The setup is done by modules to assure that the country environments don’t become out-of-sync.

Each module contains the pieces related to a functionality or feature, placed in a single deployment that is versioned. For example, version number 1 of the login module has all the parts for the login feature.

To setup a PaaS tenant, for example the Live Spain environment tenant paas-es-pro-05 for tools, the following must happen:

The first step is to setup and install the base network. This is done by running the install process of the base network module. This will install all the common parts and basic pieces needed on the tenant.

Once the base network has been installed, on top of that layer, the rest of the modules can be installed.

# 7\. Architectural Decisions {#7.-architectural-decisions}

## 7.1 Architectural Principles {#7.1-architectural-principles}

The following are the design principles of the Ether’s PaaS domain

* **AP.Ether.01 \- Zero-Downtime platform**: The platform has to be alive 24x7, the downtime has to be the closest possible to Zero, and be prepared to recover the production stability as soon as possible. The resilience of the platform is thus designed to be the highest possible

* **AP.Ether.02 \- High Availability**: This principle is directly related to the previous one, due to the fact that a High Availability is needed to achieve a Zero Downtime platform

* **AP.Ether.03 \- Immutability**: The container, components needed and applications to provide a business capability in a production environment have to be immutable, that is, once the container image is deployed it will not be modified anymore. If a change is needed, a new container, with all the necessary components will be deployed again, and the previous one will be alive for enough time to ensure the system stability and to do rollback if needed 

* **AP.Ether.04 \- Programmable infrastructure (Everything as code)**: Infrastructure, security, compliance and operations follow the same software development lifecycle practices. Code written to manage configurations and automated provisioning of infrastructure

* **AP.Ether.05 \- Continuous delivery**: There must be a DevOps practice enabled on the PaaS to follow a continuous delivery approach, to reduce the time to market in software delivery and to reduce the Gap Between Development and Operation teams 

* **AP.Ether.06 \- Test Driven Development (TDD) & Acceptance Test Driven Development (ATDD)**: These are principles to ensure that the software developed and delivered is aligned to business requirements and use cases, following a Testing First approach to be more prepared and fail fast, before arriving at the production environment

* **AP.Ether.07 \- Event Driven**: Everything has to be driven by events, and events are at the core of the integrity and the communica	tions between services and applications. They are necessary to achieve an ecosystem with a lower coupling and interconnected by asynchronous messaging, so that, if an application fails, the rest of the system will not be affected,as these applications are not connected by synchronous protocols. The system has to assume certain eventual consistency of data, time between data synchronization between the application providers and the consumers

## 7.2 Architectural Decisions {#7.2-architectural-decisions}

There are some architectural decisions related to the PaaS platform, these are the following

### 7.2.1 AD1 \- Abstracting PaaS Vendor Solutions {#7.2.1-ad1---abstracting-paas-vendor-solutions}

The use of the PaaS needs to be simplified, and this is the main reason behind the building of an abstraction layer that hides the complexity to manage Dockers with Kubernetes technology. This abstraction layer is the Waveform component, which provides an API to create, manage and orchestrate container images, using the PaaS capabilities provided by Kubernetes technology.

### 7.2.2 AD2 \- Which Coding Language to Use? {#7.2.2-ad2---which-coding-language-to-use?}

Related to the abstraction layer (Waveform) explained in the previous section, there is an architectural decision related to the programing language used to implement Waveform. Go was the selected programing language for the Waveform component. The decision to use Go instead of other languages was based on the following reasons:

* It is easy to use  
* It is a high performing programming language  
* It makes sense to keep a technological coherence: All components used by Waveform: Kubernetes, Docker, Etcd and Prometheus; are based on that same programming language

### 7.2.3 AD3 \- Which Metrics Collector to Use? {#7.2.3-ad3---which-metrics-collector-to-use?}

Prometheus was selected as the monitoring and alerting solution for the PaaS because it is considered to be the open-source solution that provides the greatest functionality, being the most widely used for these requirements, and having one of the biggest support communities for the product.

### 7.2.4 AD4 \- Which Log Emitter to Use? {#7.2.4-ad4---which-log-emitter-to-use?}

Fluentd was selected as log aggregator to consolidate logs from different sources for the PaaS. The main reason why it was selected was the fact that this software allows to have more than one emitter, while others, like Logstash, do not offer this possibility.
